english:
  title: Two Poems on the New Residence of Yi Don-nyeong at White Cloud Grotto
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I.

    Passers-by see only the verdant peaks,
    Unaware how your estate came to grace this place.
    Twisting vines conceal where serpents coil,
    High stone gates bar the wandering ox and horse.
    Though grand halls and pavilions tempt the robed officials,
    You nurture your spirit in spring and stone,
    And when guests depart and revels end,
    The mountain moon rises—a sight beyond naming.

    II.

    Once you gathered at the ancient temple grounds,
    Where ten thousand houses crowded like scales.
    When will you make the move to return?
    Today meeting you, your words bloom fragrant as laughter.
    A few acres of apricot blossoms have aged in late spring,
    While willows by the pond grow thick after rain.
    Though you dally in rustic pleasures and skip the morning court,
    Duty calls—you must still enter the halls of state.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'White Cloud Grotto (백운동): A famous scenic retreat in Korea, suggesting an idyllic natural sanctuary removed from court life.'
  - key: ''
    value: The tension between rural retreat and official duty frames both poems—a classic theme in East Asian literati poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The moon imagery in the first poem evokes the Daoist ideal of transcendence through nature.
